\section{Introduction}

The holographic approach to QCD has attracted a great deal of interest in its Top - Down and Bottom - Up approaches \cite{Erdmenger:2007cm, Brodsky:2014yha, Gursoy:2007cb, Gursoy:2007er}. In the Top - Down approach, starting from a string theory, after taking low energy limits and compacting extra dimensions, the idea is to get a theory close to QCD. In the Bottom - Up approach, well-known QCD properties are used as guidelines to build models in a gravity frame with asymptotically AdS spaces, thereby obtaining models called AdS / QCD.

In the context of Bottom - Up models, several hadron properties can be easily calculated (e.g. see \cite{Gutsche:2015xva, Gutsche:2012bp, Gutsche:2012wb, Vega:2010ns, Vega:2012iz, Brodsky:2011xx, Brodsky:2008pf, Brodsky:2007hb, Braga:2011wa, BallonBayona:2007qr, Bellantuono:2015fia, Colangelo:2011xk, BoschiFilho:2012xr}). The first version of an AdS / QCD model is known as hard wall (HW) \cite{Erlich:2005qh, DaRold:2005mxj}, where conformal invariance was broken by introducing a hard cut-off in a holographic coordinate; therefore a field associated to hadrons cannot propagate in all space. The main problem with HW models is that they do not reproduce Regge behavior because the relationship between $M^{2}$ and $n$ it is not linear. In order to improve this aspect, the soft wall (SW) model was proposed \cite{Karch:2006pv}, where conformal invariance was broken by using a dilaton field. This scalar field allows us to introduce a soft cut-off along the holographic coordinate.

The most common dilaton used is quadratic in a holographic coordinate with AdS metric, and although in this case it is possible to get a spectrum with Regge behavior in the mesonic sector, this model is not free of problems. For this reason it is interesting to study alternatives to the usual dilaton that does not destroy the spectrum.

In AdS / QCD models the spectrum is calculated by using  equations that describe hadrons which can be put in Schr\"odinger-type form; therefore using techniques that can achieve strictly isospectral potentials in Schr\"odinger equations could be very useful when exploring different alternatives for dilatons or metrics, and this offers us an opportunity to go beyond the typical choice to formulate AdS / QCD models.

There are several methods to get a family of strictly isospectral potentials for Schr\"odinger equations (e.g see \cite{AbrahamMoses, Luban:1986iv, Pursey:1986nc, Khare:1989ki, Cooper:1994eh}), and in this paper we use one developed in supersymmetric quantum mechanics (SUSY QM) \cite{Cooper:1994eh}, and as we show in this paper, each potential can be used to get a family of metrics and / or dilatons useful for work on AdS / QCD models.

Applications of SUSY QM to AdS / QCD models has been considered previously \cite{deTeramond:2014asa, Dosch:2015nwa, Dosch:2015bca, Brodsky:2015oia}
, although in a different way to ours, because these authors consider transformations that produce potentials which are not strictly isospectrals, i.e. original potential and its supersymmetric partner differ in one state. By using these transforms in \cite{deTeramond:2014asa, Dosch:2015nwa, Dosch:2015bca, Brodsky:2015oia} the authors have shown that conformal invariance in the equation that describes bound states of quarks in light front holography produce interesting superconformal relationships that connect mesonic spectrum with a spectrum of baryons in light and heavy-light sectors.

The idea proposed in this article to obtain families of metrics and / or dilatons for SW models is presented for scalar modes, but these can be implemented without difficulty in other bosonic or fermionic modes because equations that describe hadrons on the AdS side in SW models generally have the same mathematical structure.

To do this, we first obtained a Schr\"odinger type equation, and from this we got a family of strictly isospectral potentials, and associated with these potentials it is possible to extract a family of metrics and / or dilatons to AdS / QCD models. For the sake of simplicity, in this work we studied the family of dilatons related to Schr\"odinger equations that describe scalar glueballs in conventional SW models (i.e. AdS metric and quadratic dilaton) \cite{Colangelo:2007pt, Colangelo:2007if, BoschiFilho:2012xr}, in this case since the mass of mode in AdS is zero, we obtained simplified equations.

The family of dilatons that we obtained at low and high values of holographic coordinate $z$ is $\phi (z \rightarrow 0) = \kappa^{2} z^{2}$ and $\phi (z \rightarrow \infty) = \kappa^{2} z^{2}$, and by construction each dilaton produces the same spectrum for scalar glueballs, but unfortunately these dilatons have the same problem as quadratic ones at moment of building AdS / QCD models with chiral symmetry breaking. The problem with chiral symmetry breaking in AdS / QCD models has motivated the study of some modifications to these models \cite{Colangelo:2008us, Gherghetta:2009ac, Kwee:2007nq, Vega:2010ne, Vega:2011tg}, and we show how small changes in procedure to get the family of dilatons could be useful in this direction without sacrificing the spectrum.

To solve the problem associated with the right implementation of chiral symmetry breaking in SW models, some authors have considered dilatons that correspond to interpolation between $\phi (z \rightarrow 0) = \kappa_{0}^{2} z^{2}$ and $\phi (z \rightarrow \infty) = \kappa_{\infty}^{2} z^{2}$, where $\kappa_{0}^{2} \neq \kappa_{\infty}^{2}$ \cite{Gherghetta:2009ac, Chelabi:2015cwn, Chelabi:2015gpc}, and dilatons that interpolate between these limits can be obtained by introducing small changes in the isospectral potential calculated with SUSY QM transforms as we discuss in this work.

This article contains five sections. In section II we show briefly how to obtain the spectrum for scalar hadrons with SW models that considers an asymptotically AdS metric and an arbitrary z-dependent dilaton. In section III the method we use to get a family of strictly isospectral potentials in the context of SUSY QM is discussed, and we explain how we used this to get a differential equation that allowed us to extract a family of metrics and / or dilatons. As an example, we present in detail the scalar glueball case with an AdS metric and we obtain a family of dilatons. In section IV we discuss the main problem in AdS / QCD models with chiral symmetry breaking, and some possible solutions suggested in the literature. And then we show an extension of the procedure discussed in section III in order to get dilatons able to solve the problem presented in SW models with quadratic dilatons. And finally, in section V we present our conclusions and some future perspectives for additional work in this area.







